## Overview

Short-Form Indexed Memory Architecture (SIMA) is an experimental memory architecture designed to improve the efficiency of long-term memory retrieval in AI systems.

The central hypothesis is:

> A memory system should not need to retrieve the full representation of every potentially relevant memory in order to determine which memories are actually relevant.

SIMA separates:

1. Persistent memory storage
2. Memory retrieval representation
3. Memory indexing
4. Memory ranking
5. Full memory expansion
6. Context assembly

Instead of searching and loading full memory objects immediately, SIMA first searches compact, structured representations and progressively expands only the memories that are likely to be relevant.

